<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I work across the inner south-west corridor regularly. I understand who is buying in Graceville, what motivates them, and how a property positioned well against Chelmer and Sherwood comparables can drive genuine buyer competition. That corridor knowledge is what converts a well-presented home into a strong result.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Graceville's most sought-after streets run between Graceville Avenue and the station, where tree-lined blocks on flat-to-gently-rising land attract families who have outgrown Annerley or Moorooka and are ready to commit to the inner south-west long-term. Homes with original character retained, including VJ walls, timber floors, high ceilings and wide verandahs, consistently outperform renovated-to-budget alternatives at comparable land sizes. The proximity to Chelmer creates a persistent buyer overflow: buyers searching in Chelmer whose budget does not quite stretch will often pivot to Graceville and move with conviction when they find the right property.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <div style="flex:1; min-width:200px; background:#fff; padding:1.75rem; border-left:3px solid #b98229; border-radius:16px;">
